# Membly Flutter Project Rules

## Project Overview
Membly is a memory card matching game with a cyberpunk/tech aesthetic theme. Players act as "Data Repair Technicians" fixing corrupted data by matching cards within time limits.

## Core Technical Constraints
- **NO freezed package or part syntax**
- **State Management**: Use setState only (no Provider, Riverpod, Bloc, etc.)
- **Data Storage**: shared_preferences for local storage only
- **NO local image assets** (assets/images/)
- **NO cached_network_image**
- **NO user account features**
- **NO external custom fonts** (use system fonts only)
- **Icons**: Use font_awesome_flutter package

## Architecture Guidelines
Follow simplified Clean Architecture:
```
lib/
├── main.dart
├── core/
│   ├── constants/
│   ├── utils/
│   └── themes/
├── data/
│   ├── models/
│   └── local/
├── domain/
│   └── entities/
└── presentation/
    ├── screens/
    ├── widgets/
    └── providers/
```

## Design System
**Theme**: Static Flow (Deep Focus) - Cyberpunk/Tech aesthetic

### Colors (Hex Codes)
- Primary Background: `#1A1D26` (Midnight Blue)
- Card Background: `#353B48` (Slate Gray)
- Primary Action: `#6C5CE7` (Electric Purple)
- Accent/Highlight: `#00CEC9` (Mint Green)
- Text: `#DFE6E9` (Mica White)
- Danger/Warning: `#FF4757` (Red)

### Typography
- Primary Font: Rajdhani (tech/display) - weights: 400, 600, 700
- Body Font: Inter - weights: 300, 400, 600
- Use Google Fonts package

## Game Mechanics Summary
- **5 Levels** with increasing difficulty (3×4 to 6×5 grids)
- **Time-based challenges** (45s to 120s)
- **Combo system** for consecutive matches
- **Star rating** based on remaining time (1-3 stars)
- **Haptic feedback** for match success/failure
- **Observation phase** (optional first level only)

## Code Style Requirements
1. Use descriptive variable names (English)
2. Add comments for complex logic in English
3. Keep widget build methods under 100 lines (extract sub-widgets)
4. Use const constructors where possible for performance
5. Implement proper dispose() for Timers and controllers
6. Handle edge cases (pausing, rapid tapping, etc.)

## Animation Guidelines
- Card flip: 500ms duration with cubic bezier easing
- Combo indicator: Pop-in animation with fade out
- Timer bar: Smooth 1s transitions, color shift at <30% time
- Result modal: Fade in with scale animation
- All animations should feel snappy but not rushed

## State Management Pattern
Since we only use setState:
- Game logic should be in StatefulWidget classes
- Complex game state can be in a separate GameController class
- Use callbacks for child-to-parent communication
- Keep state as local as possible

## Data Persistence
Use shared_preferences for:
- Level unlock status (bool per level)
- Best scores per level (int)
- Star ratings per level (int, 0-3)
- Settings (sound, vibration, language)
- Total games played, achievements

## Performance Considerations
- Dispose timers properly
- Use RepaintBoundary for particle effects
- Optimize card grid rendering with Keys
- Avoid rebuilding entire screen on timer tick

## UI/UX Requirements
- iPhone 15 Pro frame simulation (390×844px)
- Dynamic Island at top
- Status bar with time and icons
- Home indicator bar at bottom
- Particle background effect
- Smooth screen transitions
- Lock interactions during animations

## Testing Checklist
Before committing code, verify:
- [ ] No freezed/part syntax used
- [ ] Only setState for state management
- [ ] No image assets referenced
- [ ] Timers are disposed
- [ ] Rapid tap handling works
- [ ] Pause/resume functions correctly
- [ ] Local storage saves/loads properly
- [ ] All animations are smooth
- [ ] Color scheme matches design system

